## Registering with chap-core

The generated `main.py` calls `.with_registration()` on the builder, so when
the service starts with `SERVICEKIT_ORCHESTRATOR_URL` set in the environment
it registers itself with chap-core and sends keepalive pings. Example
docker-compose fragment:

```yaml
services:
  {{ PROJECT_SLUG }}:
    build: .
{% if BASE_IMAGE == "chapkit-r-inla" %}
    platform: linux/amd64
{% endif %}
    environment:
      SERVICEKIT_ORCHESTRATOR_URL: http://chap:8000/v2/services/$$register
      # SERVICEKIT_REGISTRATION_KEY: ${SERVICEKIT_REGISTRATION_KEY:-}  # shared secret, optional
    depends_on:
      chap:
        condition: service_healthy
```

Without those env vars the call no-ops — `python main.py` locally just runs
the service without trying to register.

## Configuration

Edit the `{{ PROJECT_CLASS_NAME }}Config` class in `main.py` to add or adjust
typed fields. At runtime chapkit serialises the validated config to
`config.yml` in the workspace; your scripts read it via whatever YAML
parser they already use (`yaml.load_file` in R, `yaml.safe_load` in Python).

### `config.yml` layout (`config_format`)

`ShellModelRunner` is wired with `config_format="chap_core"` so the generated
`config.yml` matches chap-core's `ModelConfiguration` shape:

```yaml
prediction_periods: 3
additional_continuous_covariates: [rainfall, mean_temperature]
user_option_values:
  n_lags: 3
  precision: 0.01
```

Reserved fields (`prediction_periods`, `additional_continuous_covariates`) stay
at the top level; everything else you add to the config class nests under
`user_option_values`. This is what MLproject-authored scripts from the
`chap-models` ecosystem already expect — they reach for
`config["user_option_values"]["<option>"]` (Python) or
`config$user_option_values$<option>` (R) unchanged.

If your scripts are new or you prefer a flat layout, change `config_format` to
`"flat"` in `main.py` and read fields directly as top-level keys:

```yaml
prediction_periods: 3
additional_continuous_covariates: [rainfall, mean_temperature]
n_lags: 3
precision: 0.01
```

The flat layout is the default for `chapkit init` scaffolds; it's a good fit
when you control the scripts and don't need chap-core compatibility. Pick one
layout and keep your scripts aligned with it.

